HEADWORD: Heterotopy
<hw>Het`er*ot"o*py</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Hetero-</ets> + Gr. <?/
place: cf. F. <ets>h⟦eacute⟧t⟦eacute⟧rotopie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A deviation from the natural position; -- a term
applied in the case of organs or growths which are abnormal in
situation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A deviation from the natural
position of parts, supposed to be effected in thousands of years, by the
gradual displacement of germ cells.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 691 --></p>

<p><ent>Heterotricha</ent>⟦br⟧
